text:
The modern way is flexbox on the parent — three lines:

```css
.parent {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center; /* horizontal */
  align-items: center;     /* vertical */
}
```

This centers `.parent`'s children both ways regardless of their size, and is what you want in the vast majority of cases.

A couple of useful variations:

**Grid** — even shorter if the parent only holds the thing you're centering:

```css
.parent {
  display: grid;
  place-items: center;
}
```

**Centering against the full viewport** (e.g. a modal or landing element) — give the parent a height to center within, since flex aligns inside the parent's box:

```css
.parent {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;
  align-items: center;
  min-height: 100vh;
}
```

**Absolute positioning** — handy when the element must be pulled out of normal flow:

```css
.child {
  position: absolute;
  top: 50%;
  left: 50%;
  transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
}
```

Reach for flexbox by default. The one gotcha is that `align-items: center` only has room to work if the parent is actually taller than the child — if vertical centering "does nothing," it's almost always because the parent has no extra height, so set a `height` or `min-height` on it.
